    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-05T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-05T22:00:00-05:00" n="177"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d177">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1075: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-06T12:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 6, 1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received June 7—3:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>773. Embassy’s 770, June 5, 8 p.m.<note n="31" xml:id="d177fn1">Not printed; see
                        Ambassador Grew’s note of June 3, 1941, <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_312">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 312</ref>.</note> American cargo at
                    Haiphong.</p>
                <p>My French colleague made strong representations to the Japanese Government in a
                    first person note dated May 31, 1941 protesting that the agreement of August 30,
                        1940<note n="32" xml:id="d177fn2">For summary of agreement, see telegram No.
                        496, September 5, 1940, 6 p.m., from the Chargé in France, <ref
                            target="frus1940v04#pg_100">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1940, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 100</ref>.</note> and the assurances
                    recently given him by the Japanese Minister for Foreign Affairs do not give the
                    Japanese military the right of confiscation and seizure in Indochinese
                    territory, the sovereign rights of France to such territory being a monopoly.
                    The note points out the responsibility of the French Government, as the
                    sovereign power, toward the foreign owners of the goods at Haiphong and states
                    that the French Government cannot accept the Japanese proposal that these goods
                    be transferred out of Indochinese territory. The note, however, proposes that an
                    arrangement be made between the two governments for the establishment of one or
                    more depots in Indochina where these goods could be stored under joint
                    Franco-Japanese control “offering every guaranty of security”.</p>
                <p>Translation of note will go forward by mail on June 14.<note n="33"
                        xml:id="d177fn3">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to the Department via Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
